  "problem_type": "Research methodology critique — requires distinguishing mathematical validity from inferential validity, and identifying where sampling assumptions break the entire statistical framework",
  "strategy": "Socratic decomposition: verify the math independently, then audit each inferential step for assumption violations. The hardest trap is confirming the margin of error looks reasonable (it does) and stopping there — the real failure is upstream, in the sampling frame.",
  "hardest_part": "Separating two distinct questions: (1) Is 60% ± 4% internally consistent math? Yes. (2) Does that math mean anything about the general population given this sample? No. The confidence interval machinery is only valid for probability samples — applying it to a convenience sample doesn't produce a shrunken claim, it produces a meaningless one. The subtle trap is that '56% > 50%' looks like a strong buffer, making the conclusion *feel* robust when the entire inferential apparatus is broken.",
  "solution": "The conclusion is invalid. Three compounding failures:\n\n1. FATAL — Sampling frame bias: Drawing from a company's own customer email list is not a random sample of the general population. Existing customers have already revealed a preference for this company (they bought from it). Surveying them about Brand A vs Brand B — especially if Brand A is the company's own brand — is measuring prior behavior, not population preference. This alone disqualifies any inference about 'the majority of the population.'\n\n2. FATAL — Margin of error misapplied: The ±4% MOE and 95% confidence interval are defined within frequentist statistics for random probability samples only. A convenience sample (email list) violates the independence and representativeness assumptions those formulas require. The correct statement is not 'the true value is 60% ± 4%' — it is 'we have no valid statistical basis to generalize beyond this sample at all.'\n\n3. MODERATE — Non-response bias: Even within the email list, respondents self-select. People with strong positive feelings are more likely to complete surveys. This further inflates the apparent preference for Brand A beyond even the list's inherent bias.\n\nWhat the study can validly claim: '60% of the customers who responded to our email survey prefer Brand A.' That's a finding about engaged existing customers — useful for retention analysis, not population inference.\n\nThe 56% lower bound (60% - 4%) appearing comfortably above 50% is a numerical red herring. It provides false security by making the math look rigorous when the foundational sampling assumption that makes the math meaningful was never satisfied."
